WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.440
Thanks, everybody. Okay, so my talk is entitled Asynchronous Programming in R, but I have

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:17.799
to give a little disclaimer. It's sort of, but not really about asynchronous programming

00:00:17.799 --> 00:00:26.760
in R. When I was developing the materials for this talk, I realized I couldn't... Asynchronous

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:31.200
programming is such a huge topic, I would have a hard time really explaining it in the

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:37.759
way that I found satisfying in 20 minutes. And then I thought about all these other topics

00:00:37.759 --> 00:00:41.919
that come along with asynchronous programming, in my experience and the stuff that I work

00:00:41.919 --> 00:00:48.240
on. So there's also parallelism, concurrency, and event-driven programming. So let me define

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:52.840
these for you in case you're not really familiar with these. So asynchronous programming is

00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:57.480
when you call a function, it doesn't block. So normally, when you're writing your R code

00:00:57.480 --> 00:01:01.799
and you're running it, it steps through, it does each thing, and if you do something that

00:01:01.799 --> 00:01:06.879
takes a long time, like, let's say, you tell R to go download a file, it stops there, and

00:01:06.879 --> 00:01:13.919
then once the file is downloaded, it continues and your script continues to run. In an asynchronous

00:01:13.919 --> 00:01:19.320
program, you might, if there's an asynchronous download, what it would do is, you're essentially,

00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:22.760
it would say, hey, go download this file, some other thing in the computer, go download

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:27.040
the file, and the code would keep running, and then later you'd check, hey, is my file

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:31.839
downloaded, or maybe you might say, or it might run a callback and tell you, hey, the

00:01:31.839 --> 00:01:36.480
file is done now. That's asynchronous programming. Parallelism is when you do multiple things

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:41.720
at the same time. That's very common on modern computers with multiple cores. Concurrency

00:01:41.720 --> 00:01:45.639
is when it seems like you're doing multiple things at the same time, but you might not

00:01:45.639 --> 00:01:49.599
actually be doing multiple things at the same time. So if you're familiar with JavaScript

00:01:49.599 --> 00:01:54.199
in a web browser, that's single-threaded, and it can seem like a web page is doing a

00:01:54.199 --> 00:01:59.360
lot of things at once, but it's really splitting its time in between different tasks and switching

00:01:59.360 --> 00:02:05.480
between them very quickly, so it just seems like it's doing things in parallel. And finally,

00:02:05.480 --> 00:02:11.039
there's event-driven programming, where you have events that occur, there might be some

00:02:11.039 --> 00:02:18.039
outside signal, and that causes some code to run. So I was thinking about this, and

00:02:18.039 --> 00:02:21.279
asynchronous programming was too big, and so I thought I'd try to talk about all of

00:02:21.279 --> 00:02:24.759
these a little bit, or at least actually a common thread that runs through all of them,

00:02:24.759 --> 00:02:31.759
which is a package called Later. And Later was originally created by Joe Chang, and I

00:02:31.759 --> 00:02:34.919
don't know if it's a coincidence, but it was a conversation with him that helped me settle

00:02:34.919 --> 00:02:41.919
on this topic. So thanks, Joe. All right, so I'm gonna show you a demo here of... Let's

00:02:41.919 --> 00:02:50.199
see if I can make this go away. Try to make this large enough to... Well, it'll be sort

00:02:50.199 --> 00:02:56.199
of... Wow. It's semi-visible. All right, so let's say... Well, you don't have to see the

00:02:56.199 --> 00:03:01.559
specific code, the exact code here. Let's say I'm creating a data frame called data,

00:03:01.559 --> 00:03:08.279
and I've populated it with some X and Y values, and this plot magically appeared in RStudio

00:03:08.279 --> 00:03:13.759
here. And if I modify it, so I square all the X values, that plot redraws, and now I

00:03:13.759 --> 00:03:19.839
have a parabola shape here. And I can do the same with Y, and if I restore data to what

00:03:19.839 --> 00:03:28.479
it was before, it re-plots again. So there's something going on here. It's not any magic

00:03:28.479 --> 00:03:36.720
from RStudio, the IDE, but it involves later. This is... And what you're seeing here is

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:40.919
sort of, at least from the user perspective, this is event-driven programming. So I'm not

00:03:40.919 --> 00:03:46.119
telling it to re-plot every time I change data, but every time I change data, it causes

00:03:46.119 --> 00:03:50.039
this plotting code to re-execute. And I ran that, actually, ahead of time, before I started

00:03:50.039 --> 00:03:56.639
this talk, and I'll show it to you in a little bit. But let's talk about... Let's talk about

00:03:56.639 --> 00:04:03.399
what the later package does. So later provides something called an event loop. An event loop

00:04:03.399 --> 00:04:07.960
is a queue of functions that will run in the future, and it's very similar to setTimeout

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:13.880
in JavaScript, if you're familiar with JavaScript. And if this is confusing to you, I will show

00:04:13.880 --> 00:04:21.920
you a very simple example of how later is used. So you load the later package. I'm setting

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:27.600
a flag to tell me when I'm... To signal when something is done. And then I say, later,

00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:35.640
run this function here, which prints out a message and updates the flag, after five seconds.

00:04:35.640 --> 00:04:40.279
And then at the end, I'll say, while I'm not done, run now. It means keep running these

00:04:40.279 --> 00:04:46.920
functions that are in this event loop, in this queue. So let's do this. Let's run this

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:54.119
stuff here. And you won't be surprised to see that after five seconds, it prints out

00:04:54.119 --> 00:04:58.760
this message. Hello, world. And I know there's people out there who have already figured

00:04:58.760 --> 00:05:04.559
out how to write this in about six lines of code to implement this. So this part is not

00:05:04.559 --> 00:05:10.000
really that difficult. But what later... What you might be a little bit more surprised to

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:18.200
see is that if I run this same code here, and I don't do run now, and we wait five seconds,

00:05:18.200 --> 00:05:25.679
it will also print hello, world. So later has some C code that runs. And when your R

00:05:25.679 --> 00:05:30.480
console is idle, when the call stack is empty and you're not running anything else, it will

00:05:30.480 --> 00:05:41.480
continue running this event loop. Okay. So that plot watching code that I showed... Or

00:05:41.480 --> 00:05:46.880
that... You saw the plot watcher before. And this is the code. So what it does is, first...

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:50.839
It's pretty simple. So I'm just setting data to null and the last value to null. And then

00:05:50.839 --> 00:05:58.440
I have this function called plot watch. And if the data's not null, and if it's different

00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:03.839
from the last value, then plot it, and then update the last value. So that's all really

00:06:03.839 --> 00:06:10.640
standard R code. The thing that's different is, right here, I call later plot watch. So

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:17.119
this function is rescheduling itself to run after a quarter second. And then after we

00:06:17.119 --> 00:06:20.720
define the function, we have to kick it off. We have to get it started by invoking the

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:28.160
function once. And then... And it's doing what's sort of... I guess you might call it

00:06:28.160 --> 00:06:31.959
a polling loop, where it just keeps running every quarter of a second. And every time

00:06:31.959 --> 00:06:41.480
data changes, it executes the plotting code. So later also has a C API. This is important

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:44.760
when you're doing a lot of this... When you're doing asynchronous programming. Because a

00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:49.839
lot of times, you have to interface with external libraries. So from C code, you can call later

00:06:49.839 --> 00:06:56.559
to schedule a C function to execute. There's a C function later. And that C function that

00:06:56.559 --> 00:07:03.760
you scheduled to execute can in turn call an R function. And also, another very important

00:07:03.760 --> 00:07:08.839
point is that this function... The later function is thread safe. So you can have another thread

00:07:08.839 --> 00:07:15.079
schedule something to run. It can schedule an R function to run.

00:07:16.079 --> 00:07:22.559
Okay. So that's a brief overview of later. What it does is pretty simple, but it unlocks

00:07:22.559 --> 00:07:27.359
a lot of possibilities. So here's some real world uses of later. And I'm gonna show you

00:07:27.359 --> 00:07:32.959
some stuff... Some demos and explain how some of these things work.

00:07:32.959 --> 00:07:38.600
So one thing that we've worked on recently is a WebSocket client. WebSocket is a protocol

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:48.640
for basically for communicating between computers. Through a... Well, through a fancy web server.

00:07:48.640 --> 00:07:55.320
So this is how it's used. So I create a WebSocket. I say WebSocket new and connect to the server.

00:07:55.320 --> 00:08:02.440
And then I tell it... Hey, when you receive a message, invoke this function. So this is

00:08:02.440 --> 00:08:07.160
event driven programming here. But it doesn't actually call this function right away. And

00:08:07.200 --> 00:08:12.200
what it does... This function will print out, hey, I've received this... Whatever the message is.

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:18.079
All right. So I've set up that event handler. And then at the end, I can say... I can tell

00:08:18.079 --> 00:08:24.480
it to send hello world. So let's see this in action. Now, what it's doing is not very

00:08:24.480 --> 00:08:31.480
surprising. Will not be very surprising. So if you haven't... If you can't see it, this

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:35.799
is the same code that you saw before. And so I sent hello world, and what I received

00:08:35.799 --> 00:08:40.479
back is that same string reversed. So it's talking to a WebSocket server that takes a

00:08:40.479 --> 00:08:44.559
string, reverses it, and sends it back. So it's just doing this really basic transformation

00:08:44.559 --> 00:08:51.840
on it. All right. Now, the way that this works internally

00:08:51.840 --> 00:08:56.559
is used as polling, similar to that plot watcher that we... Or the data watcher that we had

00:08:56.559 --> 00:09:02.840
before. So we have this arrow representing time. And several times per second, we're

00:09:03.280 --> 00:09:07.039
polling and we're checking for any... If there's any input or output that has happened on this

00:09:07.039 --> 00:09:14.039
WebSocket. Now, at some arbitrary point in time, in R, you might tell it to send a message.

00:09:14.799 --> 00:09:20.919
Send hello world. And that gets... That puts it in this output queue. But that output queue

00:09:20.919 --> 00:09:25.559
isn't handled until this polling event here. And when we get to the polling event, that

00:09:25.559 --> 00:09:31.599
actually calls out to a C++ library that handles all this input and output stuff. And it sends

00:09:31.599 --> 00:09:38.599
a message to the server. When that happens, the server sends a message back. And then

00:09:39.239 --> 00:09:45.119
that message sits in the input queue until the next polling event happens. And when that

00:09:45.119 --> 00:09:48.739
occurs, then it calls the on message handler. And it prints out they have received this

00:09:48.739 --> 00:09:54.200
hello world reversed. And I just... In this particular slide, the blue indicates that

00:09:54.200 --> 00:09:58.479
this is something that was triggered by the polling event that later provided.

00:09:59.479 --> 00:10:02.679
Okay. So that's how the WebSocket package works. At least that's how the CRAN version

00:10:02.679 --> 00:10:08.679
of WebSocket works. On GitHub, there's actually... The development version of WebSocket has been

00:10:08.679 --> 00:10:14.359
changed to use threads. Actually, let me show you one thing real quick about this. So if

00:10:14.359 --> 00:10:20.039
you're familiar with this sort of programming, you know that polling is not the ideal way

00:10:20.039 --> 00:10:24.760
to do this. There's a little bit of latency that can occur between these events here.

00:10:24.760 --> 00:10:30.880
And it also... If you're doing a lot of polling really quick, it can use CPU time that shouldn't

00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:36.919
be... That really shouldn't be used. But it's simple to implement. So the development version

00:10:36.919 --> 00:10:43.919
of WebSocket is threaded. This is... And so there's two threads. There's this main R thread.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:50.400
And then it launches another thread that handles the input and output. All right. So if I tell

00:10:50.440 --> 00:10:56.440
it to send a message from... And that happens in R. What it does is it calls the C function...

00:10:56.440 --> 00:11:01.479
Or C++ function send, which is thread safe. Which tells the IO thread, hey, I want you

00:11:01.479 --> 00:11:06.919
to send this message. And the IO thread at this point will be idle. And so it will deal

00:11:06.919 --> 00:11:12.320
with this request right away. Send the message to the server. Server sends something back.

00:11:12.320 --> 00:11:19.320
And if the IO thread is idle then, it will immediately use later to tell the R thread...

00:11:19.919 --> 00:11:24.400
This is the C function later. To tell R thread, hey, handle this message that I just got.

00:11:24.400 --> 00:11:29.440
And if R thread is sitting idle at that point, it will print it out. If R thread is busy

00:11:29.440 --> 00:11:36.440
at that time, like represented by that red bar there, then it will... It will wait until

00:11:36.919 --> 00:11:41.000
it's done doing whatever computation it's doing. And then it will handle that queued

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:48.000
function. All right. So these are two common ways of handling input and output. Asynchronous

00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:55.840
IO. With polling and with threads. All right.

00:11:57.440 --> 00:12:03.520
Another use that we have is a web server called HTPUV. This package, you might have heard

00:12:03.520 --> 00:12:10.520
of it before. It has an awkward name. It underlies Shiny and Plumber. And to start a web server,

00:12:12.080 --> 00:12:16.320
it's actually very simple. You just say start server. You give it the port you want to listen

00:12:16.320 --> 00:12:21.919
to it on. And then this function here, which it's a callback that gets invoked when an

00:12:21.919 --> 00:12:27.479
event happens. An incoming request occurs. So when you get an incoming HTTP request,

00:12:27.479 --> 00:12:34.440
it calls this function and passes in this object called rec. And in this case, I'm just

00:12:34.440 --> 00:12:38.039
having it create a web page that has the time and the path that was requested. And then

00:12:38.039 --> 00:12:42.359
it returns some other HTTP stuff along with that. So you can imagine that you can use

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:49.000
this in all sorts of different ways. It just will execute an R function whenever you get

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:56.000
an HTTP request. So I'll show you this real quick in action. What it will do is also not

00:12:56.440 --> 00:13:01.799
surprising, since I've already talked about it. Gives you the time and the path that was

00:13:01.799 --> 00:13:07.599
requested. So that was just slash. I could say R studio conf. And then it prints out

00:13:07.640 --> 00:13:14.640
that path there. All right. Now I'm just gonna show you some other cool stuff. Some fun stuff.

00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:23.440
So I also started before this... Before I started doing the talk, I started up another

00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:30.960
HTTP via application, which provides a remote R console, a REPL. So I can say, you know,

00:13:31.960 --> 00:13:38.960
1, 1 plus 1, sum of 1 through 10. And this is causing R code to execute. So this is actually

00:13:42.919 --> 00:13:48.719
using WebSocket connection. It's... The web browser sends this string over the WebSocket.

00:13:48.719 --> 00:13:53.520
And then the R process gets the string, it evaluates it, captures the output, and then

00:13:53.520 --> 00:14:00.080
sends it back. So that's what's happening here. The interesting thing about this is

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:03.320
it's actually running in the same R process that we've been doing all the rest of this

00:14:03.320 --> 00:14:10.320
stuff. So if I change data to be... That's why I say data X... Data X squared. That did

00:14:15.760 --> 00:14:22.760
not work at all. Oh, there it goes. Okay. All right. So this is running in the same

00:14:23.039 --> 00:14:30.039
R process. All right. And of course, you're familiar with Shiny. Shiny is based on HTTP

00:14:31.080 --> 00:14:37.080
so I can run this Shiny app here, which is displaying the same data. And I can... If

00:14:37.080 --> 00:14:41.479
I randomize it, it'll... You know, if I click this button to randomize, it does... You've

00:14:41.479 --> 00:14:46.400
seen this sort of thing with a Shiny app. And again, these are connected here. So when

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:50.320
I randomize the data, I'm using poor Shiny programming practices where I'm modifying

00:14:50.320 --> 00:14:57.320
a global variable. But for this demo, it's good. And it's changing that plot right there.

00:14:58.320 --> 00:15:03.239
Okay. So that's a taste of some of the things that are possible. There's one other thing

00:15:03.239 --> 00:15:10.239
I want to show. Using a package called Chromote, which is a headless Chrome web browser package,

00:15:13.880 --> 00:15:17.359
which uses a lot of asynchronous programming. And I won't go into depth about it right now.

00:15:17.359 --> 00:15:23.599
I just want to show some other fun stuff that you can do. So I can start a Chromote session.

00:15:23.599 --> 00:15:30.599
I'll navigate to the same application. And I'll take a screenshot of it. And when it

00:15:32.880 --> 00:15:38.119
takes a screenshot, it actually will cause that screenshot to appear in this viewer pane

00:15:38.119 --> 00:15:42.880
here. This is not the Shiny app here. This is a screenshot of a Shiny app. If you see,

00:15:42.880 --> 00:15:48.440
I can drag this around here. And just to prove to you that it's actually... Oops. I tried

