indicates that it was selected, which is what I was doing over there. All right. So that's

00:16:25.599 --> 00:16:32.599
the fun demos. All right. So let's get back to what we saw here. So we saw this WebSocket

00:16:34.679 --> 00:16:40.640
server that reverses strings. Web server that shows you the time. Web server with this remote

00:16:40.640 --> 00:16:45.919
R console, which you can use while you're running a Shiny application. Running a Shiny

00:16:46.039 --> 00:16:51.239
app. We had this plot data watcher. And we had this headless Chrome client. All of these

00:16:51.239 --> 00:16:55.719
use later. That's what makes it all possible for them to run concurrently. And this is

00:16:55.719 --> 00:17:02.719
all in one R process. Okay. So one thing... I took a look at the later CRAN page. And

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.680
I looked at the packages that we're using later. And one thing I noticed was that even

00:17:11.680 --> 00:17:14.719
though it's been out for a couple of years, there's not that many packages that use it.

00:17:14.719 --> 00:17:20.280
And all of them are maintained by people that work at RStudio. So I'm hoping that...

00:17:20.280 --> 00:17:24.959
We have a lot of this knowledge internally from... We've got battle scars working on

00:17:24.959 --> 00:17:31.959
this stuff. But hopefully... Hopefully if you're working on async programming or parallelism

00:17:32.239 --> 00:17:39.239
or concurrency, this will be useful for you. And I have the URL here. It's not... The materials

00:17:39.920 --> 00:17:46.920
aren't actually up there right now, but they will be. Thank you.

00:17:47.479 --> 00:17:54.479
Thanks, Winston. That was fascinating. I can assure you that I am using your work. I have

00:17:58.359 --> 00:18:03.199
promote writing on a scheduled basis to take photographs of the work my colleagues are

00:18:03.199 --> 00:18:10.199
doing. For those of you that are leaving, we are just carrying on with questions. So

00:18:10.760 --> 00:18:17.760
please do so quietly if you can. Question number one. Does Latit deal with the issues

00:18:18.560 --> 00:18:25.560
of tail call stack optimization that could arise from the recursive event loop format?

00:18:26.160 --> 00:18:30.079
It does not. That's actually a great question. You have to be... I wanted to mention it,

00:18:30.119 --> 00:18:33.680
but I didn't have time. If you're going to be calling the function itself, you have to

00:18:33.680 --> 00:18:39.439
make sure not to create any closures that will keep increasing the depth of the call

00:18:39.439 --> 00:18:46.439
stack. So you have to create a function outside of your function that you're calling.

00:18:46.560 --> 00:18:52.040
And the second question is, if Latit is running and you want to run another... What happened?

00:18:52.040 --> 00:18:57.400
Oh, there we go. And you want to run another line of code, does the new line you are running

00:18:57.400 --> 00:19:02.800
jump ahead of later, or does it wait those five seconds to run?

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:07.959
So if you... It will jump ahead of later. So after five seconds have elapsed, even whatever

00:19:07.959 --> 00:19:12.479
you've written, whatever you've done before, it won't wait an extra five seconds. It will

00:19:12.479 --> 00:19:18.760
wait for five seconds total, unless R is occupied at the moment, that callback would occur.

